"Mok Y.S., Demidyuk V., Whitehead J.C.","Decomposition of hydrofluorocarbons in a dielectric-packed plasma reactor",2008,"Journal of Physical Chemistry A","112","29",,"6586","6591",,,10.1021/jp8020084,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-49149100020&partnerID=40&md5=84b11dd9b7d8dffe38717143c688178c","Department of Chemical Engineering, Cheju National University, Aradong, Jeju 690-756, South Korea; School of Chemistry, University of Manchester, Oxford Road, Manchester, M13 9PL, United Kingdom","Mok, Y.S., Department of Chemical Engineering, Cheju National University, Aradong, Jeju 690-756, South Korea; Demidyuk, V., School of Chemistry, University of Manchester, Oxford Road, Manchester, M13 9PL, United Kingdom; Whitehead, J.C., School of Chemistry, University of Manchester, Oxford Road, Manchester, M13 9PL, United Kingdom","This study investigated the decomposition of hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) having high global warming potentials by using a dielectric-packed-bed nonthermal plasma reactor with barium titanate beads as the packing material. The target HFCs were 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane (HFC-134a) and 1,1-difluoroethene (HFC-132a). The effects of several parameters such as reaction temperature, oxygen content, and initial concentration on the HFC decomposition efficiency were evaluated. There was essentially no temperature dependence of the HFC decomposition efficiency in the range 150-250°C. The optimum oxygen content for HFC decomposition was found to be about 0.5 vol %, Variations in the initial concentration did not affect the decomposition efficiency. The decomposition products were analyzed, and some decomposition pathways were elucidated. The energy requirements for the decomposition of HFC-134a and HFC-132a were found to be 0.038 and 0.062 mol MJ-1, respectively, based on the initial concentrations of 200 and 120 ppm (parts per million, volumetric). © 2008 American Chemical Society.",,"Barium; Concentration (process); Global warming; Inductively coupled plasma; Nonmetals; Oxygen; Plasma applications; Plasmas; Decomposition efficiency; Decomposition pathways; Decomposition products; Energy requirements; Global warming potentials; HFC-134a; Hydrofluorocarbons; Initial concentration; Nonthermal plasma reactors; Oxygen contents; Packed-bed; Packing materials; Plasma reactors; Reaction temperatures; Temperature dependences; Tetrafluoroethane; Barium titanate",,,,,,"Takita, Y., Tanabe, T., Ito, M., Ogura, M., Muraya, T., Yasuda, S., Nishiguchi, H., Shihara, T., (2002) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res, 41, p. 2585; Takizawa, K., Takahashi, A., Tokuhashi, K., Kondo, S., Sekiya, A., (2006) J. Fluorine Chem, 127, p. 1547; Ohno, M., Ozawa, Y., Mizuno, A., Ono, T., (2007) Res. Inst. Environ. Technol, 36, p. 427; Ohno, M., Ozawa, Y., Ono, T., (2007) Int. J. Plasma Environ. Sci. Technol, 1, p. 159; Ogata, A., Kim, H.-H., Futamura, S., Kushiyama, S., Mizuno, K., (2004) Appl. Catal. B: Environ, 53, p. 175; Fitzsimmons, C., Ismail, F., Whitehead, J.C., Wilman, J.J., (2000) J. Phys. Chem. A, 104, p. 6032; Ricketts, C.L., Wallis, A.E., Whitehead, J.C., Zhang, K., (2004) J. Phys. Chem. A, 108, p. 8341; Futamura, S., Gurusamy, A., (2005) J. Electrostatics, 63, p. 949; Spiess, F.-J., Chen, X., Brock, S.L., Suib, S.L., Hayashi, Y., Matsumoto, H., (2000) J. Phys. Chem. A, 104, p. 11111; Chang, M.B., Yu, S.J., (2001) Environ. Sci. Technol, 35, p. 1587; Kang, H.-C., (2002) J. Ind. Eng. Chem, 8, p. 488; Futamura, S., Einaga, H., Zhang, A., (2001) IEEE Trans. Ind. Appl, 37, p. 978; Yen, S.J., Chang, M.B., (2001) Plasma Chem. Plasma Process, 21, p. 469; Wallis, A.E., Whitehead, J.C., Zhang, K., (2007) Appl. Catal. B, 74, p. 111; Arkady, G., Ogata, A., Futamura, S., Mizuno, K., (2003) J. Phys. Chem. A, 107, p. 8859; Park, J.-Y., Park, J.-G., Kim, J.-S., Rim, G.-H., Kim, K.-S., (2003) IEEE Trans. Plasma Sci, 31, p. 1349; Demidyuk, V., Whitehead, J.C., (2007) Plasma Chem Plasma Process, 27, p. 85; Hanst, P.L., Hanst, S.T., (1993) Infrared Spectra for